zed": false, "mention": "methylmercury", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9998134970664978, "span": {"begin": 1759, "end": 1772}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Cerebral cortical astrocytes", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8516333103179932, "span": {"begin": 1806, "end": 1834}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:30785"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "methylmercury", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9998207688331604, "span": {"begin": 1853, "end": 1866}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:25322"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "methylmercruy", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9990862607955933, "span": {"begin": 1956, "end": 1969}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:32285"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "[U-13C] lactate", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9988284111022949, "span": {"begin": 2005, "end": 2020}}, {"id": ["mesh:D019344"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "lactate", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9957744479179382, "span": {"begin": 2040, "end": 2047}}, {"id": ["mesh:D014233"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "tricarboxylic acid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9987809658050537, "span": {"begin": 2107, "end": 2125}}, {"id": ["mesh:D028361"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "mitochondrial dysfunction", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9993565082550049, "span": {"begin": 2150, "end": 2175}}, {"id": ["mesh:D018698"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "glutamate", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.978358268737793, "span": {"begin": 2180, "end": 2189}}, {"id": ["mesh:D019344"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "lactate", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9977515339851379, "span": {"begin": 2229, "end": 2236}}, {"id": ["mesh:D019344"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "lactate", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9908905625343323, "span": {"begin": 2297, "end": 2304}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "neurons", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7371240854263306, "span": {"begin": 2353, "end": 2360}}], "text": "Porciuncula et al., (2003). Methylmercury (2-10 &micro;M) inhibits glutamate uptake in synaptic vesicles isolated from rat brain in a concentration-dependent manner (with LD50 at 50 &micro;M). It also inhibits the H+-ATPase activity in a concentration-dependent manner with similar LD50. This suggests that the vesicular glutamate uptake is impaired by methylmercury and that this effect involves the H+-ATPase.  Roos et al., (2009). Methylmercury induced ROS production in rat brain cortical slices after 2h exposure at 100 and 200 &micro;M and after 5h exposure at 50 &micro;M. Guanosine (0.5 - 5 &micro;M), ebselen (1-5 &micro;M) and diphenyl diselenide (1-5 &micro;M) blocked the methylmercury-induced ROS production. The inhibitor of NMDA receptors, MK801 (50 &micro;M) equally blocked the methylmercury-induced ROS production by two potential mechanisms of action: (i) mercury by affecting mitochondria iincreased ROS formation, which decrease glutamate uptake and consequently increased extracellular glutamate acting on NMDA receptors; (ii) The ROS formation is secondary to overstimulation of NMDA receptors, due to mercury-induced decrease in glutamate uptake.  Roos et al., (2011). Experiments performed in isolated mitochondria from rat liver slices showed that methylmercury (25 &micro;M) increased ROS production (measured by dichlorofluoroscein). Methionine treatment (50-250 &micro;M) was effective in reducing ROS formation.  Juarez et al., (2002) Microdialysis probe in adult Wistar rats showed that acute exposure to methylmercury (10, 100 &micro;M) induced an increase release of extracellular glutamate (9.8 fold at 10 &micro;M and 2.4 fold at 100 &micro;M). This extracellular glutamate level remained elevated at least 90 min following methylmercury exposure.  Allen et al., (2001). Cerebral cortical astrocytes were treated with methylmercury (1 &micro;M for 24h or 10 &micro;M for 30 min) and loaded with [U-13C] glutamate. In the methylmercruy-treated group, a decrease of&nbsp; [U-13C] lactate was observed. This lactate can only be derived from mitochondrial metabolism, via the tricarboxylic acid, showing a link between mitochondrial dysfunction and glutamate metabolism. In addition, the decreased lactate production might be detrimental to surrounding cells, since lactate has been shown to be an important substrate for neurons.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:30:54 +0000 2026"}